eveltype="part" searchtype="LEGISLATION PART" subdoc="false" toc-caption="PART 12  DISCONTINUANCE, WITHDRAWAL, DISMISSAL AND SETTING ASIDE OF ORIGINATING PROCESS [rr 12.1&#x2013;12.11]"><leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT12.D2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="division" searchtype="LEGISLATION DIVISION" subdoc="false" toc-caption="DIVISION 2  WITHDRAWAL OF APPEARANCE OR PLEADING [rr 12.5, 12.6]">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading><desig searchtype="DIV-NUM"><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT12.D2" type="ext"/>DIVISION 2</designum></desig><title searchtype="DIV-TITLE"> WITHDRAWAL OF APPEARANCE OR PLEADING [rr 12.5, 12.6]</title></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-5"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 12.5] r 12.5 Withdrawal of appearance (cf SCR Part 21, rule 1)">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-5" type="ext"/>[r 12.5]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Withdrawal of appearance (cf SCR Part 21, rule 1)</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>12.5</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text> An active party may withdraw an appearance by leave of the court.</text></p>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTE"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.12-5.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTE</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.12-5-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[12.5.5] Leave to withdraw appearance"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.12-5-5" type="ext"/>[12.5.5] </edpnum><title>Leave to withdraw appearance</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>Leave to withdraw an appearance is appropriate where it has been entered by mistake or where a solicitor acts without proper instructions: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002538" spanref="cr002538-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WLR"/><ci:volume num="1"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1978"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="1184"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Firth v John Mowlem &amp; Co Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002538-001" status="unval">[1978] 1 WLR 1184</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="242160" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002539" spanref="cr002539-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC201009033"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Evergreen Tours Pty Ltd v McLaren</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> [2010] NSWSC 1362; <ci:span spanid="cr002539-001"> BC201009033</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="507623" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (submitting appearance filed before obtaining merits advice); compare <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002540" spanref="cr002540-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC200904263"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Hilton v Gidley</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> [2009] NSWSC 383; <ci:span spanid="cr002540-001"> BC200904263</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="474137" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (submitting appearance filed in error &#x2014; no arguable defence &#x2014; leave to withdraw refused); see also r 6.11 and note at [6.11.7]. Although leave is not restricted to such cases: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002541" spanref="cr002541-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="QB"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1981"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="368"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Rothmans of Pall Mall (Overseas) Ltd v Saudi Arabian Airlines Corp</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002541-001" status="unval">[1981] QB 368</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="242159" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; leave to withdraw is generally not appropriate where the appearance was entered deliberately and on proper advice: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002542" spanref="cr002542-001"><ci:reporter value="All ER"/><ci:volume num="3"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1968"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="26"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Somportex Ltd v Philadelphia Chewing Gum Corp</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002542-001">[1968] 3 All ER 26</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="143648" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. It will be particularly inappropriate to grant leave to withdraw where the applicant has previously taken an active part in the proceedings: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002543" spanref="cr002543-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC200706614"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Garsec v His Majesty The Sultan of Brunei</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> [2007] NSWSC 882; <ci:span spanid="cr002543-001" status="unval"> BC200706614</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="441876" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (prior unsuccessful application for summary judgment &#x2014; no subsequent leave to withdraw appearance). Conversely, it may be appropriate to grant leave to withdraw a submitting appearance where a co-defendant and judgment debtor, who was previously the moving party in appeal proceedings, is no longer legally represented in the proceedings: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002544" spanref="cr002544-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC201201588"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Tory v Megna</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> [2012] NSWCA 41; <ci:span spanid="cr002544-001"> BC201201588</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="548100" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (leave granted &#x2014; subject to conditions that require security for costs of the appeal).</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level></leg:comntry>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-6"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 12.6] r 12.6 Withdrawal of matter in defence or subsequent pleading (cf SCR Part 21, rules 3 and 5; DCR Part 18, rule 2; LCR Part 17, rule 2)">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-6" type="ext"/>[r 12.6]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Withdrawal of matter in defence or subsequent pleading (cf SCR Part 21, rules 3 and 5; DCR Part 18, rule 2; LCR Part 17, rule 2)</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>12.6</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-6.1"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-6.1" type="ext"/>(1)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>A party raising any matter in a defence or subsequent pleading may withdraw the matter at any time.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-6.2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-6.2" type="ext"/>(2)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>Despite subrule (1), a party may not withdraw any admission, or any other matter that operates for the benefit of another party, except with the consent of the other party or by leave of the court.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-6.3"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-6.3" type="ext"/>(3)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>A withdrawal under this rule is to be made by filing a notice of withdrawal stating the extent of the withdrawal.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-6.4"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-6.4" type="ext"/>(4)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>If the withdrawal is by consent, the notice under subrule (3) must be accompanied by a notice from each party whose consent is required by subrule (2) to the effect that the party consents to the admission or other matter being withdrawn in accordance with the notice of withdrawal.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:bodytext>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTES"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.12-6.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTES</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.12-6-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[12.6.5] Withdrawal at any time">
<glp:note><blockquote><hrule/>
<p>
<text><inlineobject attachment="web-server" filename="leg1.gif" type="image"/> Legislation cited in [12.6.5] below. LawNow subscribers click through for daily updates and historical versions.</text><text> </text>
<text>(NSW) <ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink alttext="Click to link to LawNow Legislation" dpsi="005Y" refpt="NSW_REG_2005-418" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">Uniform Civil Procedure Rules 2005</remotelink> r 12.1, r 12.3(2).</ci:content></ci:cite></text>
</p></blockquote></glp:note><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.12-6-5" type="ext"/>[12.6.5] </edpnum><title>Withdrawal at any time</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>Withdrawal applies to a defendant who either does not wish to contest the proceedings, or does not wish to pursue a particular ground of defence. A defence may be withdrawn at any time, either before or after the commencement of the hearing and without any requirement for leave, unless the withdrawal would adversely affect the rights of the other parties arising from admissions contained in the defence. If the defence as a whole is withdrawn, the plaintiff will be entitled either to default judgment or judgment on admissions: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr002545" spanref="cr002545-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WN"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1908"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="100"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Cooper-Dean v Badham</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr002545-001" status="unval">[1908] WN 100</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>. The rule does not deal with the imposition of terms, as is the case with discontinuance of the claim by consent (
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-1" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">r 12.1</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
) and the effect of discontinuance generally (
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R12-3.2" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">r 12.3(2)</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
).</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level><level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.12-6-10" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[12.6.10] Withdrawal of admissions "><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.12-6-10" type="ext"/>[12.6.10] </edpnum><title>Withdrawal of admissions </title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>Leave is required to withdraw any formal admissions in the proceedings: see generally 
<remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.17-2-5" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">[17.2.5]</remotelink>
.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level></leg:comntry>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
